07240nam a22009735i 9783111191850DE-B159720240306014423.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20232023gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831111918507 a10.1515/97831111918502doi  a(DE-B1597)649456  a(OCoLC)1394872685  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE04a304.23223//eng/20230630eng00aMaking Spaces through Infrastructure :bVisions, Technologies, and Tensions /ced. by Marian Burchardt, Dirk Laak. 1aMünchen ;aWien : bDe Gruyter Oldenbourg, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (VIII, 268 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aDialectics of the Global ,x2570-2289 ;v1600tFrontmatter -- tOn the Series -- tContents -- t1 Making Spaces through Infrastructure – Introduction -- tI Ordering Places and People: Infrastructure Projects and their Outcomes -- t2 Intersecting Infrastructures: Imperial Technology and East African Transport Labour, c. 1900 -- t3 Playgrounds for Travellers: Infrastructure, Environment, and Spatial Transformation in the Americas, 1880s–1920s -- t4 Hydropower for a Modern Afghanistan: Soviet Aid to the Southern Neighbour in the 1960s -- t5 Reformatting a Socionatural Space: The Goulburn-Murray Irrigation District, Australia -- tII Zones of Negotiation: Infrastructures and Social Practices -- t6 The Zanjas through Different Political Regimes: Infrastructure, Space, and Society in Nineteenth-Century Los Angeles -- t7 Roads for Whom? Tourism and Infrastructure in Post-colonial East Africa -- t8 Between Worlds: Perceiving the Inner-German Border as Infrastructure, 1945–1990 -- t9 Fiction and Filter: The Emergence of Airport Transit Zones in the Twentieth Century -- t10 Staying under Bridges, Negotiating Barriers: Unhoused Berliners’ Infrastructural Practices between Spatial Exclusion and Precarious Spatial Strategies -- tIII Conflicting Spaces: Infrastructures Old and New -- t11 Dreams and Realities of Infrastructural Leapfrogging: Airspace, Drone Corridors, and Logistics in African Healthcare -- t12 The Space of Datafied Societies: A New Horizon of Colonial Expansion? -- tList of Abbreviations -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aInfrastructures are fundamental means through which societies create spaces, but little is known about the precise ways in which this occurs. How have infrastructures animated certain understandings of space? How do infrastructures stabilize, or undermine, the spatial formats in which we live, which shape our everyday practices and which regulate access to services and resources? And, conversely, how do spaces frame the ways infrastructural provision is organized? How do existing spaces shape infrastructural development and the scope and forms of access to vital services such as transport and water? In this volume, historians and sociologists draw on a range of fascinating case studies and provide compelling answers to these questions. Exploring, among others, the provision of irrigation water in nineteenth-century Los Angeles, the invention of airport transit zones, and the infrastructural practices of homeless people in Berlin, the book demonstrates how the making of spaces through infrastructure is deeply political. Intent on revealing uneven geographies of provision and hierarchies of access, the contributors highlight how infrastructures are products of global entanglements.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aInfrastructure (Economics). 4aGlobalisierung. 4aInfrastruktur. 4aRaum. 4aTechnologie.  aglobalization.  ainfrastructure.  aspace.  atechnology.1 aBurchardt, Marian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBurchardt, Marian